Neural Activity Exploration Project

Kyoungdeok Han

2025-03-14

Abstract

In experimental setting, the research aims to understand how neural activity corresponds to behavioral responses. This project explores and analyzes neural activity in four different mice acrosss multiple sessions solely focusing on the Session that displayed unique pattern ( ex) session 10 ), identifying unique clustering pattern compared to other sessions. PCA (Principal Component Analysis) is applied to analyze each different brain regions spike rate distribution. I also chose one of the sessions that doesnt show unique pattern to compare with session ( ex) session 10) using spike distributions, correlation analysis, and PCA projection. Adding on, based on neural activity pattern, I developed logistic regression models to predict feedback type. The findings provide insights that ( ex) session 10 ) shows unique and distinct neural activity pattern which could be related to specific behavioral outcomes.

Introduction

A lot of neuroscientists strive to understand how neural activity evolves in response to behavioral tasks. This project studies neural activity across multiple experimental sessions from 1 through 18, with a particular focus on the unique session which displayed unique clustering patterns possibly correlated with behavioral performance. I also used PCA (Principal Component Analysis) to reduce dimensionality and visualize neural activity. Adding on, Clustering helps determining whether session 13 differs from other sessions by far. In order to predict behavioral outcomes based on neural features, logistic regression is applied. Determing whether the sessions exhibit distinct neural characteristic or unique patterns in relation to behavioral success rate, I used that one unique session with session that is doesnt display any unique clustering pattern.

Summary of Features

  • feedback_type: Around 70% of instances indicate success, but we might need to consider potential issues.
  • contrast_left and contrast_right: Present in four distinct scenarios. In particular,
    • When left contrast > right contrast, success (1) if turning the wheel to the right and failure (-1) otherwise.
    • When right contrast > left contrast, success (1) if turning the wheel to the left and failure (-1) otherwise.
    • When both left and right contrasts are zero, success (1) if holding the wheel still and failure (-1) otherwise.
    • When left and right contrasts are equal but non-zero, left or right will be randomly chosen (50%) as the correct choice.
  • mouse_name: Affected by four factors (Cori, Frossman, Hence, Lederberg)
  • date_exp: May be useless as it is not directly correlated with success.
  • brain_area: Area of the brain where each neuron lives. Comprised of multiple factors; consideration for reduction to a smaller set of factors may be beneficial.
  • spks: Matrix of dimensions pi qi across session i for number of trials Ni.
  • time: Vector of dimension q across sessions for number of trials Ni.

Preparing the data before PCA analysis

all_sessions <- list()
for (i in 1:18) {
  all_sessions[[i]] <- data.frame(session_id = i,
                                  brain_area = session[[i]]$brain_area,
                                  spike_count = rowSums(session[[i]]$spks[[1]]))
}
df_spikes <- bind_rows(all_sessions)

df_avg_spikes <- df_spikes %>%
  group_by(session_id, brain_area) %>%
  summarize(avg_spikes = mean(spike_count, na.rm = TRUE), .groups = "drop")

df_pca <- df_avg_spikes %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = brain_area, values_from = avg_spikes, values_fill = 0)

df_pca <- df_pca %>% mutate_if(is.character, as.numeric)

pca_data <- df_pca %>% select(-session_id)

pca_data <- pca_data[, apply(pca_data, 2, var) > 0]

PCA performance for the neural spike data

pca_result <- prcomp(pca_data, center = TRUE, scale. = TRUE)

pca_df <- as.data.frame(pca_result$x)
pca_df$session_id <- df_pca$session_id

ggplot(pca_df, aes(x = PC1, y = PC2, color = factor(session_id))) +

Comparing session 13 to 17 in terms of spike distributions

Boxplot across brain areas to compare spike activity

library(ggplot2)

spike_13 <- data.frame(
  brain_area = session[[13]]$brain_area,
  spike_count = rowSums(session[[13]]$spks[[1]])
)

spike_17 <- data.frame(
  brain_area = session[[17]]$brain_area,
  spike_count = rowSums(session[[17]]$spks[[1]])
)

spike_13$session <- "Session 13"
spike_17$session <- "Session 17"
combined_data_spike <- rbind(spike_13, spike_17)

ggplot(combined_data_spike, aes(x = brain_area, y = spike_count, fill = session)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  theme_minimal() +
  labs(title = "Comparison of Spike Counts per Brain Area",
       x = "Brain Area",
       y = "Spike Count") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

Based on the plot, I suggest that Session 17 displayed less neural activity overall compared to Session 13.

The brain areas that show greater variability such as RN, PL, MS, MRN might be a part of behaviors which were more dominant during Session 13.

The less activity in Session 17 relative to Session 13 might be because of behavioral states or different experimental conditions.

Preparing data for logistic regression, employing benchmark method 1

Benchmark method 1 - Summarizing brain_area, spks, and time into a single number by getting the average over spks

n_obs = length(session[[13]]$feedback_type)

dat = tibble(
    feedback_type = as.factor(session[[13]]$feedback_type),
    decision = rep('name', n_obs),
    avg_spikes = rep(0, n_obs)
)

for (i in 1:n_obs){
    # decision 
    if (session[[13]]$contrast_left[i] > session[[13]]$contrast_right[i]){
        dat$decision[i] = '1' 
    } else if (session[[13]]$contrast_left[i] < session[[13]]$contrast_right[i]){
        dat$decision[i] = '2' 
    } else if (session[[13]]$contrast_left[i] == session[[13]]$contrast_right[i] 
               & session[[13]]$contrast_left[i] == 0){
        dat$decision[i] = '3' 
    } else{
        dat$decision[i] = '4' 
    }
    
    # avg_spks
    spks.trial = session[[13]]$spks[[i]]
    total.spikes = apply(spks.trial, 1, sum)
    dat$avg_spikes[i] = mean(total.spikes)
}

dat$decision = as.factor(dat$decision)
summary(dat)

avg_spike_area<-function(i.t,this_session){
  spk.trial = this_session$spks[[i.t]]
  area= this_session$brain_area
  spk.count=apply(spk.trial,1,sum)
  spk.average.tapply=tapply(spk.count, area, mean)
  return(spk.average.tapply)
}

Discussion

First of all, the PCA results suggests that session 13 has distinct clustering patterns compared to other sessions, potentially indicating differences in neural activity distribution. The comparison made between session 13 and 17 using the direct comparison of spike distributions and PCA projects reveals variations in neural firing rates across brain regions. For the predictive model built using logistic regression model, the model trained on neural data showed a moderate performance to classify feedback type based on spike activity possibly suggesting some brain regions may be critical in decision making process.

The exact reason for unique clustering of session 13 remains unclear. Hypothetically, if session 13 keeps showing different neural patterns, it could be due to learning effect or other experimental conditions. For further investigation, we could try to conduct additional feature selection in PCA.

What is PC score? It is the value that places each data points position along the newly defined axes that catches the most variance after PCA adjusts the original data from the data with high dimensions

For the side note, PCA was applied seperately to each session, and the top two principal component scores were explored

The PC1 explains the largest variance while PC2 explains the second-largest
